Extracting Date Parts

SQL provides functions to extract components such as year and month from date values.

SET @date_temp = DATE('2029-08-19');
SET @datetime_temp = TIMESTAMP('2029-05-18 12:50:45');

@date_temp contains only a date (YYYY-MM-DD)
@datetime_temp contains both date and time (YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS)

Method 1: Direct Functions (Most Commonly Used)

This is the simplest and most widely used approach. SQL provides direct functions for each date/time component.

SELECT
    YEAR(@date_temp)  AS year,
    MONTH(@date_temp) AS month,
    DAY(@date_temp)   AS day;

YEAR() extracts the year part = 2029
MONTH() extracts the month part = 8
DAY() extracts the day part = 19

Extracting from a DATETIME / TIMESTAMP value

SELECT
    HOUR(@datetime_temp)   AS hour,
    MINUTE(@datetime_temp) AS minute,
    SECOND(@datetime_temp) AS second;


HOUR() extracts the hour = 12
MINUTE() extracts the minute = 50
SECOND() extracts the seconds = 45


Most important interview trap question

WHERE login_time >= '2029-01-01 00:00:00'
  AND login_time <= '2029-01-31 00:00:00';


Why This Is Wrong

This condition includes only the first second of January 31st. Any login after midnight on Jan 31 is excluded, for example:

2029-01-31 09:45:00
2029-01-31 18:30:12
2029-01-31 23:59:59

this wonot capture 31 st time 

Correct and Recommended Pattern (Best Practice), use an inclusive start and an exclusive end (half-open interval):
WHERE login_time >= '2029-01-01 00:00:00'
  AND login_time <  '2029-02-01 00:00:00'